The first part of this review will discuss the topic of heterologous immunity [28] and the existing evidence that established memory T cell responses to a previously encountered pathogen can have a major impact on T cell immunodominance, protective immunity, and immunopathology during a subsequent infection with an unrelated pathogen (Fig. 1
). These also may influence allo-specific T cell activity prior to and following transplantation (Fig. 2
).
